lonial time.Ruiz argues that Ricanness—a continual performance of bodily endurance against US colonialism through different measures of time—uncovers what’s at stake politically for the often unwanted, anticolonial, racialized and sexualized enduring body. Moving among theatre, experimental video, revolutionary protest, photography, poetry, and durational performance art, Ricanness stages scenes in which the philosophical, social, and psychic come together at the site of aesthetics, against the colonization of time. Analyzing the work of artists and revolutionaries like ADÁL, Lebrón, Papo Colo, Pedro Pietri, and Ryan Rivera, Ricanness imagines a Rican future through the time travel extended in their aesthetic interventions, illustrating how they have reformulated time itself through nonlinear aesthetic practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aArts, Puerto RicanxThemes, motives. 0aGroup identity in art. 0aPostcolonialism and the artszPuerto Rico. 0aTime and artzPuerto Rico. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh  aADÁL.  aBrownness.  aDa-sein.  aEl Museo del Barrio.  aFrantz Fanon.  aGuy Debord.  aHurricane Maria.  aLolita Lebrón.  aMartin Heidegger.  aNietzsche.  aPapo Colo.  aPedro Pietri.  aPuerto Rican Nationalist Party.  aPuerto Rican.  aabsurdism.  aaesthetics.  acolonialism.  acrisis.  adeath drive.  adrama.  adreaming.  aduration.  aemergency.  aendurance.  aexistentialism.  aexperimental.  afutural.  aimagination.  alooping.  anonlinear time.  aperformance art.  aphilosophy.  apoetry.  apostcolonial.  apoverty.  aqueer.  aracialized masculinity.  arape.  aslow death.  atheater.  aunwantedness.  avideo art.  aviolence.  avulgarity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertN